quran[6]{c,v,t,f}:
59,4,"That is because they set themselves against Allah and His Messenger; and whoever sets himself against Allah should know that Allah is surely Most Stern in retribution."
59,5,"The palm-trees that you cut down or those that you left standing on their roots, it was by Allah's leave that you did so. {1} (Allah granted you this leave) in order that He might humiliate the evil-doers. {2}",footnotes:1:The reference is to the fact that the Muslims cut down or burnt many of the palm-trees that stood in the oases around the settlement of the Bani an-Nadir in order to facilitate the siege
59,6,"Whatever Allah has taken away from them and bestowed (as spoils) on His Messenger {1} for which you spurred neither horses nor camels; but Allah grants authority to His Messengers over whomsoever He pleases. Allah has power over everything. {2}",footnotes:1:From here to the end of verse 10
59,7,"Whatever (from the possessions of the towns people) Allah has bestowed on His Messenger belongs to Allah, and to the Messenger, and to his kinsfolk, and to the orphans, and to the needy, and to the wayfarer {1} so that it may not merely circulate between the rich among you. {2} So accept whatever the Messenger gives you, and refrain from whatever he forbids you. And fear Allah: verily Allah is Most Stern in retribution. {3}",footnotes:1:In the preceding verse what was pointed out was why these properties should not be distributed among the fighting army like the spoils
59,8,"It also belongs to the poor Emigrants who have been driven out of their homes and their possessions, {1} those who seek Allah's favour and good pleasure and help Allah and His Messenger. Such are the truthful ones.",footnotes:1:This implies those people who at that time had been expelled from Makkah and other parts of Arabia only because they had embraced Islam. Before the conquest of the territory of the Bani an-Nadir these emigrants had no permanent means of sustenance. Therefore
59,9,"It also belongs to those who were already settled in this abode (of Hijrah) {1} having come to faith before the (arrival of the) Muhajirun (Emigrants).They love those who have migrated to them and do not covet what has been given them; they even prefer them above themselves though poverty be their own lot. {2} And whosoever are preserved from their own greed, such are the ones that will prosper. {3}",footnotes:1:This implies the Ansar. In other words
